PATTERN 1 — SINGLETON
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Intent: Guarantee exactly one instance of a class and provide global access to it.
Use when: Logger, configuration store, hardware driver wrapper, thread pool manager.
Do NOT use when: You want testability (singletons make mocking hard), or when
                  multiple instances may be needed later. Prefer dependency injection.

    class Logger {
    public:
        static Logger& instance() {
            static Logger inst;   // Meyers Singleton — thread-safe since C++11
            return inst;
        }
        void log(std::string_view msg) {
            std::lock_guard lock(mutex_);
            std::clog << msg << '\n';
        }
        Logger(const Logger&) = delete;
        Logger& operator=(const Logger&) = delete;
    private:
        Logger() = default;
        std::mutex mutex_;
    };

